Use ASP.NET Core's **`WebApplicationFactory<T>`** from `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing`. It hosts your app in-memory with a full HTTP pipeline but no real network port.

**Setup (test project `.csproj`):**
```xml
<PackageReference Include="Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing" Version="9.*" />
<PackageReference Include="xunit" Version="2.*" />
```

**Example test:**
```csharp
public class McpIntegrationTests : IClassFixture<WebApplicationFactory<Program>>
{
    private readonly HttpClient _client;

    public McpIntegrationTests(WebApplicationFactory<Program> factory)
    {
        _client = factory.CreateClient();
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task Initialize_ReturnsCapabilities()
    {
        var request = new
        {
            jsonrpc = "2.0",
            id = 1,
            method = "initialize",
            @params = new
            {
                protocolVersion = "2025-03-26",
                capabilities = new { },
                clientInfo = new { name = "test-client", version = "1.0" }
            }
        };

        var response = await _client.PostAsJsonAsync("/mcp", request);

        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        var body = await response.Content.ReadFromJsonAsync<JsonElement>();
        Assert.Equal("2025-03-26",
            body.GetProperty("result").GetProperty("protocolVersion").GetString());
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task ToolsCall_ExecutesTool()
    {
        // Initialize first (required by MCP)
        await InitializeSession();

        var request = new
        {
            jsonrpc = "2.0",
            id = 2,
            method = "tools/call",
            @params = new { name = "my-tool", arguments = new { input = "hello" } }
        };

        var response = await _client.PostAsJsonAsync("/mcp", request);

        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        var body = await response.Content.ReadFromJsonAsync<JsonElement>();
        Assert.False(body.GetProperty("result").GetProperty("isError").GetBoolean());
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- `WebApplicationFactory<Program>` boots your real `Program.cs` startup in-process
- `CreateClient()` gives you an `HttpClient` that talks to the in-memory server
- No ports, no network — tests are fast and parallelizable
- If you use Streamable HTTP (SSE), use `SendAsync` with `HttpCompletionOption.ResponseHeadersRead` and read the SSE stream from `response.Content.ReadAsStreamAsync()`
- Override services (e.g., mock databases) via `factory.WithWebHostBuilder(b => b.ConfigureServices(...))`

This tests the full middleware pipeline, routing, serialization, and MCP protocol handling end-to-end.
